    "author_association": "COLLABORATOR",
    "body": "> The ls utility sorts by name by default, so I think it's not unreasonable for folks to generally expect that PS's Get-ChildItem does the same.\r\n\r\nEvery time I see an appeal to Unix it makes me nervous. \r\nWhatever part of Unix we touch, we always find in its history discussions or even claims that it works wrong but it doesn't get fixed because it's been working for _years_.\r\nI sometimes get the feeling that Unix consists entirely of deviations from concepts, violations of standards and bugs in implementation which are declared as Unix standards! ðŸ˜º \r\n\r\n_PowerShell 1.0 appeared as a rethinking of previous experiences (including Unix) based on the most advanced concepts of the time._\r\nIs it worth referring to Unix as the benchmark in this situation (I am not talking about minor inconsistencies in implementation, but about concepts)? No.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately the conceptual development process of PowerShell stopped a long time ago. It got bogged down in the swamp of everyday life and backward compatibility. Although the number of incompatible changes is already so great that it makes no sense to talk about backward compatibility.\r\n\r\n_We should be discussing and trying to implement modern innovative concepts more than pink colored letters or ala old school Unix behavior._",
